The amount currently shown in the records is approximately ${{ (surplus_amount or 0)|money }}. You should confirm the exact figure directly with the district clerk before filing anything.

A few things worth knowing about how Texas handles these claims:

Under Texas Tax Code Sections 34.03 and 34.04, the officer holding the excess proceeds must provide notice, and a claimant must file a petition before the second anniversary of the tax sale date. If no timely petition is filed, the proceeds are distributed to the taxing units. The claim is filed in the court that ordered the sale, and the court may schedule a hearing before approving distribution.

The court will generally require documents showing your ownership or lien interest in the property and, if you are acting for someone else or for an estate, your authority to do so. Review any fee agreement carefully before signing anything.

We help property owners and eligible claimants gather the required documentation and prepare the petition and supporting materials for filing in the court that ordered the sale. If you have questions about whether you have a valid claim, what documents you will need, or whether anyone else may have a competing interest in the funds, we are glad to walk through it with you.

You are also welcome to contact the district clerk of {{ county_name }} County directly to pursue the claim on your own. There is no obligation to respond to this letter.

